article.description: Tina Thompson scored 31 points to help the Houston Comets clinch a playoff birth.
article.headline: Thompson rockets Comets past Storm, into No. 3 spot
article.linkText: Thompson rockets Comets past Storm, into No. 3 spot
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Tina Thompson powered the Houston Comets into the
WNBA playoffs.

Thompson, playing in just her second game after missing 13
contests with a calf injury, scored 31 points and had seven
rebounds to help Houston beat Seattle 89-72 on Saturday.

Houston (18-16) clinched the third seed in the Western
Conference and will play Sacramento in the first round. Seattle
(18-16), seeded fourth, will begin the playoffs against Los
Angeles. Houston earned the third seed by winning all three games
this season against Seattle.

"To be able to finish third is a great accomplishment," said
Houston coach Van Chancellor. "I didn't care how we got in, but it
feels awfully good to get in through the front door. We didn't have
to come through the back door. We're still at the same table
eating, but we're just going to enjoy it more."

Betty Lennox led the Storm with 16 points and Sue Bird added 14.

"Our mindset was just to win the game," said Lennox, who
scored 14 of her 16 points in the first half. "We just didn't do
that. We didn't execute our offense right, and we didn't play
aggressive defense. We just beat ourselves."

After missing out on a chance to clinch two nights earlier with
a 111-110 triple overtime loss to Phoenix, the Comets left little
doubt they wanted in the postseason.

Houston opened the second quarter with a 13-0 run to extend its
lead from seven to 20. Thompson scored five points in the burst,
with Sheryl Swoopes capping the spree with a layup with 6:14 left
in the second quarter to put Houston ahead 38-18.

Seattle closed to 10 in the third quarter on a 3-pointer by Sue
Bird with 4:04 left, but Houston increased the lead to 70-54 with a
6-0 run. The Comets started the fourth quarter with a 10-1 run,
four by Thompson, to make it 83-61 and put the game away.

Thompson became only the third player in franchise history to
score 30 or more points in consecutive games after she scored a
career-high 37 points Thursday against Phoenix.

"It was all or nothing tonight," said Thompson, who scored 20
points in the first half. "If we didn't win tonight, then we would
have had to wait to see what Phoenix was doing, and we don't want
anyone else to control our destiny. I think that was the attitude
coming in. Plus, we just wanted to get into the playoffs."

Playing without leading scorer Lauren Jackson for the second
straight game, Seattle shot 49 percent. The Storm also committed 19
turnovers, which Houston turned into 21 points.

"I think losing this game makes us hungry," said Seattle coach
Anne Donovan. "I don't think we've lost any confidence because we
didn't have Lauren, and we faced a team that wasn't going to be
denied tonight in Houston."

Swoopes and Michelle Snow had 16 points apiece for Houston. In
her final regular-season WNBA game, Dawn Staley finished with five
points and seven assists. After the game, the Comets honored Staley
with a 30-minute ceremony highlighting each level of her basketball
career.

"I'm really thankful to the organization for putting on such a
classy event," said Staley about the postgame ceremony. "They've
won four WNBA championships, so everything they do is first class.
Hopefully, I can help bring a fifth won here."
